<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en" id="home">

<meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8" />

<head>
  <title>OneUptime | Runbooks — response procedures that actually run themselves.</title>
  <meta name="description"
    content="OneUptime Runbooks are reusable response procedures — manual checklists and automated steps — that attach to incidents, alerts, and scheduled maintenance the moment they're created.">
  <%- include('head', {
    enableGoogleTagManager: typeof enableGoogleTagManager !== 'undefined' ? enableGoogleTagManager : false
  }) -%>
</head>

<body>
  <%- include('nav') -%>
  <main id="main-content">

    <!-- Hero -->
    <div class="relative isolate overflow-hidden bg-white" id="runbooks-hero">
      <div class="absolute inset-0 -z-10 h-full w-full bg-white bg-[linear-gradient(to_right,#f0f0f0_1px,transparent_1px),linear-gradient(to_bottom,#f0f0f0_1px,transparent_1px)] bg-[size:4rem_4rem] [mask-image:radial-gradient(ellipse_60%_50%_at_50%_0%,#000_70%,transparent_110%)]"></div>

      <div class="py-20 sm:py-28 lg:py-32">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 lg:px-8">
          <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center">
            <p class="text-sm font-medium text-teal-600 mb-4">Response procedures — done your way</p>

            <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-5xl lg:text-6xl">
              Runbooks that run themselves
            </h1>
            <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
              Define an ordered list of steps — manual checklists, JavaScript, HTTP calls, or bash. Attach them to incidents, alerts, or scheduled maintenance by rule. Responders see exactly what's been done and what's left.
            </p>

            <div class="mt-10 flex items-center justify-center gap-x-6">
              <a href="/accounts/register"
                class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-white shadow-sm hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors">
                Get started
              </a>
              <a href="/enterprise/demo" class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900 hover:text-gray-600 transition-colors">
                Request demo <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
              </a>
            </div>

            <div class="mt-12 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-x-8 gap-y-3 text-sm text-gray-500">
              <span>Manual checklists</span>
              <span class="hidden sm:inline text-gray-300">|</span>
              <span>JavaScript &amp; bash</span>
              <span class="hidden sm:inline text-gray-300">|</span>
              <span>HTTP calls</span>
              <span class="hidden sm:inline text-gray-300">|</span>
              <span>Auto-trigger on incidents</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <%- include('logo-roll') -%>

    <!-- How it works -->
    <div class="relative bg-gray-50 py-24 sm:py-32">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center mb-16">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-4xl">
            One feature, three roles in one
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-gray-600">
            A runbook is a recipe. The same recipe can be ticked off by a human, executed by a script, or both — interleaved.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-teal-50 text-teal-700 flex items-center justify-center font-semibold">1</div>
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Author the steps</h3>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
              Add steps one at a time. Manual steps are checklist items. JavaScript runs in an isolated VM. HTTP and bash give you escape hatches when you need them.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-teal-50 text-teal-700 flex items-center justify-center font-semibold">2</div>
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Hook it to events</h3>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
              Create a Runbook Rule on Incidents, Alerts, or Scheduled Maintenance. Match by title or description regex. When the event is created, the matching runbooks start automatically.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-teal-50 text-teal-700 flex items-center justify-center font-semibold">3</div>
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Respond &amp; tick off</h3>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
              The runbook execution lives on the incident page. Automated steps run inline; manual steps wait for someone to tick them. Every output is captured — no lost-tab postmortems.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Feature grid -->
    <div class="relative bg-white py-24 sm:py-32">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center mb-16">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-4xl">
            Built for actual incident response
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-gray-600">
            Not a workflow engine wearing a checklist costume.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-gray-900">Four step types</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
              Manual checklist · Sandboxed JavaScript (via isolated-vm) · HTTP request · Bash (gated). Mix and match in any order.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-gray-900">Snapshot on start</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
              When a runbook starts, its steps are snapshotted onto the execution. Editing the template afterwards never mutates an in-flight run — postmortems stay accurate.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-gray-900">Per-event executions</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
              Every run is attached to its incident, alert, or maintenance event. See past runs on the event page; open one to view step-by-step output and tick off remaining steps.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-gray-900">Pattern-based rules</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
              Match by title/description regex per entity type. "Anything matching <code>db-</code> in title → run the DB failover runbook." Skip patterns to match everything.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-gray-900">Manual override</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
              "Run Runbook" button on every incident, alert, and maintenance event. Pick a runbook and go — no need to define a rule first.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-gray-900">Captured output</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
              Stdout, return values, HTTP responses, error messages — all retained on the execution. No more "what did that script actually print?"
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CTA -->
    <div class="bg-gray-50 py-20">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl text-center px-6">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-4xl">
          Stop writing "step 1: SSH to box" in Slack
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-gray-600">
          Codify your response. Make it runnable. Trigger it automatically. Get back to sleep.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-8 flex items-center justify-center gap-4">
          <a href="/accounts/register"
            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-white shadow-sm hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors">
            Start free
          </a>
          <a href="/enterprise/demo"
            class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900 hover:text-gray-600 transition-colors">
            Talk to us &rarr;
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </main>
  <%- include('footer') -%>
</body>

</html>
